<HEADLINE> Mozambique Gets 30 Million U.S. Dollar Aid for Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has gained this week
some 30 million U.S. dollars in aid for reconstruction of the
infrastructures damaged by floods earlier this year in the
southeastern African country, said reports reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao, who signed the aid
agreements respectively with the Dutch and Danish ambassadors to
Mozambique, said that the 20 million dollars disbursed by the
Netherlands will be used in minimizing the impact of the floods in
education, water and sanitation sectors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 10 million dollar funds from Denmark have been
earmarked for the rehabilitation of electricity infrastructure
destroyed in the February and March floods.
</P>
<P>
At a donors conference held in May in Rome on Mozambique's post-
flood reconstruction, the Netherlands pledged a 45-million-dollar
assistance while Denmark promised 10 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dutch Ambassador to Mozambique, Arie Van Der
Wiel, the amount offered by the Netherlands will be disbursed in
two tranches during the 2000-2001 fiscal year, while the remaining
25 million dollars will be available after evaluation of the
progress of the reconstruction activities.
</P>
<P>
At the Rome conference, the international community pledged 452.
9 million dollars for reconstruction of Mozambique's
infrastructure. So far only 130 million dollars has been disbursed.
</P>
